{"id":"1904.05378","submitter":"Rui Pan","authors":"Rui Pan, Zhaoyu Fei, Tian Qiu, Jing-Ning Zhang, and H. T. Quan","title":"Quantum-classical correspondence of work distributions for initial\n  states with quantum coherence","comments":"12 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The standard definition of quantum fluctuating work is based on the\ntwo-projective energy measurement, which however does not apply to systems with\ninitial quantum coherence because the first projective energy measurement\ndestroys the initial coherence, and affects the subsequent evolution of the\nsystem. To address this issue, several alternative definitions, such as those\nbased on the full counting statistics and the Margenau-Hill distribution, have\nbeen proposed recently. These definitions seem ad hoc because justifications\nfor them are still lacking. In the current study, by utilizing the quantum\nFeynman-Kac formula and the phase space formulation of quantum mechanics, we\nprove that the leading order of work distributions is equal to the classical\nwork distribution. Thus we prove the validity of the quantum-classical\ncorrespondence of work distributions for initial states with quantum coherence,\nand provide some justification for those definitions of work. We use an exactly\nsolvable model of the linearly dragged harmonic oscillator to demonstrate our\nmain results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Apr 2019 18:14:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-12"}
